ce:section.ce:para:
Herein, the outstanding merits of NGQDs and SO2 have been utilized for designing an ingenious combination therapy strategy, with the aim to enhance the antitumor effect through the synergistic effects of SDT and GT (Scheme 1
                     ). To this end, self-assembled Gd-NGQDs/BTS@PLGA-PEG nanomedicine was elaborately constructed by a double emulsion-solvent evaporation method. With the aid of blockpolymer poly(lactide-co-glycolide)-b-poly(ethylene glycol) (PLGA-PEG), the emerging sonosensitizer NGQDs, acid-responsive prodrug BTS and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) contrast agent Gd3+ were integrated through self-assembly. The obtained Gd-NGQDs/BTS@PLGA-PEG can induce the production of highly toxic ROS under US irradiation for SDT, and meanwhile controllably release SO2 in response to acidic environment for GT. More importantly, the SO2 release leads not only to SOD inhibition and subsequent increase in superoxide anion levels, but also to intracellular GSH depletion and glutathione peroxidase 4 (GPX4) enzyme inactivation. Therefore, this novel combined strategy of SDT and SO2-based GT significantly amplifies oxidative stress by inhibiting tumor antioxidant system, which effectively stimulates the destruction of mitochondrial function and promotes the cell apoptosis. On the basis of in vitro combined therapy, bilateral tumor models were further established to investigate the synergistic therapeutic effects of SDT and SO2 on the inhibition of tumor growth. In vivo treatment results showed that only a single intravenous injection of Gd-NGQDs/BTS@PLGA-PEG and a subsequent single US irradiation could effectively inhibit the bilateral tumors. Gd-NGQDs/BTS@PLGA-PEG can also serve as a promising T
                     1-weighted MRI contrast agent for tumor imaging and the guidance of combined SDT/GT. This innovative synergistic SDT/GT model explored in our work is expected to provide an effective strategy for conquering deep tumors.
